00:01:39.650 --> 00:01:41.830
you a little bit about
Measurement Lab, a project

00:01:41.830 --> 00:01:44.720
we've been supporting to empower
users with tools to

00:01:44.720 --> 00:01:48.840
measure their broadband
internet connection.

00:01:48.840 --> 00:01:51.440
DOMINIC HAMON: So yeah, I'd love
to talk about M-Lab, or

00:01:51.440 --> 00:01:52.520
Measurement Lab.

00:01:52.520 --> 00:01:54.950
The first thing to do is
to describe what it is.

00:01:54.950 --> 00:01:56.065
Because I'm sure there's
a lot of people out

00:01:56.065 --> 00:01:57.620
there who don't know.

00:01:57.620 --> 00:02:02.260
It's a collaboration between
a number of companies and

00:02:02.260 --> 00:02:04.360
researcher-driven.

00:02:04.360 --> 00:02:07.780
It empowers internet users,
researchers, and regulators

00:02:07.780 --> 00:02:10.960
with freely-accessible open data
coming from open-source

00:02:10.960 --> 00:02:14.810
tools, initially about network
performance, but also with

00:02:14.810 --> 00:02:17.480
some very interesting
information about network

00:02:17.480 --> 00:02:21.900
neutrality and keeping
the internet open.

00:02:21.900 --> 00:02:26.540
So M-Lab's founding principle
is one of openness.

00:02:26.540 --> 00:02:28.750
And that means making room
for real science.

00:02:28.750 --> 00:02:31.970
So it allows us to have
independent peer-reviews on

00:02:31.970 --> 00:02:35.060
data, reproduction of
existing results.

00:02:35.060 --> 00:02:36.480
We can build on top of existing

00:02:36.480 --> 00:02:38.370
research that's out there.

00:02:38.370 --> 00:02:40.965
And it gives us long-term
validity and credibility.

00:02:40.965 --> 00:02:43.720
And the way that we do this is
we have a publicly documented

00:02:43.720 --> 00:02:46.440
server platform that is
completely open-source.

00:02:46.440 --> 00:02:49.410
We have experiments built
by researchers that are

00:02:49.410 --> 00:02:50.690
completely open-source.

00:02:50.690 --> 00:02:53.790
And all of the data gets
pushed publicly, freely

00:02:53.790 --> 00:02:57.100
available for anyone to
analyze and dig into.

00:02:57.100 --> 00:03:02.620
And as I have on a slide here,
showing you where all of the

00:03:02.620 --> 00:03:05.030
servers are around the world.

00:03:05.030 --> 00:03:07.280
And as you can see, we're
globally distributed.

00:03:07.280 --> 00:03:09.810
There's a few places we haven't
quite got to yet.

00:03:09.810 --> 00:03:10.860
But we're working--

00:03:10.860 --> 00:03:13.860
as we see users wanting to be in
those areas, we're starting

00:03:13.860 --> 00:03:16.480
to build those up as
much as we can.

00:03:16.480 --> 00:03:20.582
So the M-Lab platform, to give
a brief overview, consists of

00:03:20.582 --> 00:03:21.530
some measurement tools.

00:03:21.530 --> 00:03:23.860
These are the experiments that
are built by researchers.

00:03:23.860 --> 00:03:26.970
And they run against the
platform, against these

00:03:26.970 --> 00:03:28.620
globally-distributed servers.

00:03:28.620 --> 00:03:31.210
And then all of the data is
pushed into a number of

00:03:31.210 --> 00:03:35.410
backends, like a Google Cloud
Storage and BigQuery.

00:03:35.410 --> 00:03:38.710
And this allows end-users, like
policymakers, analysts,

00:03:38.710 --> 00:03:42.230
other researchers, and end-users
of the internet to

00:03:42.230 --> 00:03:44.070
look into what the state
of the internet

00:03:44.070 --> 00:03:46.730
is on a global scale.

00:03:46.730 --> 00:03:50.010
And when I say data, we
have a lot of data.

00:03:50.010 --> 00:03:52.590
It is completely
public domain.

00:03:52.590 --> 00:03:54.080
There's a bunch of ways
to access the

00:03:54.080 --> 00:03:56.840
data, through web APIs.

00:03:56.840 --> 00:04:01.250
There is the raw data, which
we've collected about 630

00:04:01.250 --> 00:04:03.730
terabytes since January 2010.

00:04:03.730 --> 00:04:06.160
It's completely non-aggregated.

00:04:06.160 --> 00:04:08.650
There's been no processing
done at all.

00:04:08.650 --> 00:04:10.630
It's just there to
be looked at.

00:04:10.630 --> 00:04:13.370
And that comes from about
200,000 tests

00:04:13.370 --> 00:04:15.200
running every day.

00:04:15.200 --> 00:04:17.769
As well as that, we've formatted
some in a slightly

00:04:17.769 --> 00:04:20.959
easier to access, SQL-like
interface.

00:04:20.959 --> 00:04:24.310
And there we have 700 billion
rows of data to dig into,

00:04:24.310 --> 00:04:26.650
which includes some
geolocation data.

00:04:26.650 --> 00:04:28.620
So you can start to look
at the data by

00:04:28.620 --> 00:04:32.380
country, by city, by ISP.

00:04:32.380 --> 00:04:34.740
We have some future plans.

00:04:34.740 --> 00:04:38.430
Making the data collection
easier to use, putting more

00:04:38.430 --> 00:04:42.540
and more data into BigQuery, and
rolling out some standards

00:04:42.540 --> 00:04:45.910
for data collection, as well, so
that not only us, but other

00:04:45.910 --> 00:04:49.590
platforms that are collecting
data, can be cross-correlated.

00:04:49.590 --> 00:04:51.730
We're also looking at extending
the server platform

00:04:51.730 --> 00:04:53.110
to more places.

00:04:53.110 --> 00:04:55.530
And basically, we want M-Lab to
be the go-to platform for

00:04:55.530 --> 00:04:58.470
network measurement
and analysis.

00:04:58.470 --> 00:05:01.240
There's a couple of interesting
visualizations of

00:05:01.240 --> 00:05:04.390
the data that I think it would
be good to dig into.

00:05:04.390 --> 00:05:07.530
The first was this one
that was built by--

00:05:07.530 --> 00:05:10.210
looking at a tool
called Glasnost.

00:05:10.210 --> 00:05:13.250
And Glasnost looks at what's
called traffic shaping, which

00:05:13.250 --> 00:05:19.650
is when ISPs will change the
priority on certain data going

00:05:19.650 --> 00:05:21.990
through their networks,
sometimes positively,

00:05:21.990 --> 00:05:23.460
sometimes negatively.

00:05:23.460 --> 00:05:29.020
And this research on this map
shows that across the world,

00:05:29.020 --> 00:05:31.160
the amount of traffic shaping
that is going on

00:05:31.160 --> 00:05:33.270
for different protocols.

00:05:33.270 --> 00:05:36.030
And so you can break
it down to HTTP.

00:05:36.030 --> 00:05:38.560
And you can see which countries
are manipulating

00:05:38.560 --> 00:05:40.500
HTTP traffic.

00:05:40.500 --> 00:05:44.110
And similarly, you can do the
same for, say, email, and a

00:05:44.110 --> 00:05:44.770
bunch of other things.

00:05:44.770 --> 00:05:47.800
You can dig in by clicking on
a country, as well, and

00:05:47.800 --> 00:05:49.920
looking at different providers
and how much they're

00:05:49.920 --> 00:05:51.340
manipulating the traffic.

00:05:51.340 --> 00:05:53.100
Now this isn't always negative,
I should stress.

00:05:53.100 --> 00:05:55.270
They are sometimes prioritizing
the traffic.

00:05:55.270 --> 00:05:57.970
But this is very interesting for
end-users to understand,

00:05:57.970 --> 00:06:03.040
for example in the US, which
providers are manipulating

00:06:03.040 --> 00:06:05.290
data in which ways.

00:06:05.290 --> 00:06:08.810
Also, we can look
at performance.

00:06:08.810 --> 00:06:11.900
Again, to enable end-users to
understand what they're

00:06:11.900 --> 00:06:13.630
getting compared to
other people.

00:06:13.630 --> 00:06:18.190
So here, just looking at this
chart of download throughput,

00:06:18.190 --> 00:06:20.550
we can compare everything
around the world.

00:06:20.550 --> 00:06:21.940
We can break down by country.

00:06:21.940 --> 00:06:24.460
So here we have the United
States and Sweden for

00:06:24.460 --> 00:06:26.290
comparison.

00:06:26.290 --> 00:06:29.190
We can compare down to region
as well, which in the

00:06:29.190 --> 00:06:33.130
US means per state.

00:06:33.130 --> 00:06:37.100
So, for example,
if I can find--

00:06:37.100 --> 00:06:38.250
let's not do all countries.

00:06:38.250 --> 00:06:42.390
Let's say, the United States
And we can say, California

00:06:42.390 --> 00:06:44.180
versus, say, Iowa.

00:06:44.180 --> 00:06:47.130
And we can just look at the
download throughput there.

00:06:47.130 --> 00:06:48.610
There's a bunch of other
things that we

00:06:48.610 --> 00:06:49.490
can look at as well.

00:06:49.490 --> 00:06:51.960
And the nice thing about this
is that we can also look at

00:06:51.960 --> 00:06:53.270
other statistics.

00:06:53.270 --> 00:06:55.020
For example, if we wanted
to look at the download

00:06:55.020 --> 00:07:00.090
throughput versus the upload
throughput to see who gets the

00:07:00.090 --> 00:07:03.730
better balance, we can break
this down like this.

00:07:03.730 --> 00:07:07.230
We can also look at how many
tests were run in terms of the

00:07:07.230 --> 00:07:08.050
size of the dots.

00:07:08.050 --> 00:07:10.170
So then you start to get an idea
of how you can really dig

00:07:10.170 --> 00:07:12.570
into the data, Rhode Island
looking particularly good for

00:07:12.570 --> 00:07:14.820
upload throughput.

00:07:14.820 --> 00:07:16.620
And the nice thing about this
is, as well, you can look at

00:07:16.620 --> 00:07:18.470
changes over time.

00:07:18.470 --> 00:07:20.700
And as I said, this is all
coming from the public data

00:07:20.700 --> 00:07:22.880
that's been collected
on M-Lab.

00:07:22.880 --> 00:07:24.650
Now because this is
freely-available, one of the

00:07:24.650 --> 00:07:27.600
things that would be great is to
have developers really dig

00:07:27.600 --> 00:07:29.880
into this data.

00:07:29.880 --> 00:07:32.790
We have a lot of researchers
who are very interested in

00:07:32.790 --> 00:07:35.330
building tools and generating
experiments

00:07:35.330 --> 00:07:37.190
and generating data.

00:07:37.190 --> 00:07:40.250
And some researchers are also
looking at analyzing the data

00:07:40.250 --> 00:07:42.280
across some of these
experiments.

00:07:42.280 --> 00:07:45.060
But any developer could jump
into this and build some

00:07:45.060 --> 00:07:47.270
really interesting
visualizations and get out

00:07:47.270 --> 00:07:50.650
some very interesting
conclusions about what the

00:07:50.650 --> 00:07:52.175
state of the internet
actually is.

00:07:52.175 --> 00:07:55.860
And I would love to hear from
any developers that want to

00:07:55.860 --> 00:07:58.060
dig into this data, and
would happily help

00:07:58.060 --> 00:07:59.580
them figure that out.

00:07:59.580 --> 00:08:02.150
So that's the overview
of M-Lab.

00:08:02.150 --> 00:08:05.060
DEREK SLATER: So, Dominic, all
of the data comes from users

00:08:05.060 --> 00:08:07.450
running tests on the website?

00:08:07.450 --> 00:08:10.380
Or where do they go to
run these tests?

00:08:10.380 --> 00:08:12.840
DOMINIC HAMON: They can go to
measurementlab.net, which has

00:08:12.840 --> 00:08:15.650
a link to all the experiments
that are run.

00:08:15.650 --> 00:08:18.040
Some of them are applications
that can be installed.

00:08:18.040 --> 00:08:20.330
Some of them run through
the web browser.

00:08:20.330 --> 00:08:21.950
It's really a per-experiment
thing.

00:08:24.460 --> 00:08:26.760
DEREK SLATER: People run tests
on speedtest.net or other

00:08:26.760 --> 00:08:27.750
sorts of platforms.

00:08:27.750 --> 00:08:31.290
What are the key differences for
researchers or for people

00:08:31.290 --> 00:08:33.100
who are looking to
analyze the data,

00:08:33.100 --> 00:08:34.580
compared to those platforms?

00:08:34.580 --> 00:08:35.890
DOMINIC HAMON: Yeah, that's
actually a really good point,

00:08:35.890 --> 00:08:37.200
so thank you for asking.

00:08:37.200 --> 00:08:43.080
So speedtest.net is great for
figuring out what your

00:08:43.080 --> 00:08:45.640
internet looks like.

00:08:45.640 --> 00:08:48.360
One of the things that we don't
get with speedtest.net

00:08:48.360 --> 00:08:50.810
is the open methodology.

00:08:50.810 --> 00:08:53.700
So it's not entirely clear
exactly how that

00:08:53.700 --> 00:08:55.630
data is being produced.

00:08:55.630 --> 00:08:58.270
It's also a little trickier
to get a hold of the raw,

00:08:58.270 --> 00:09:00.200
unaggregated data.

00:09:00.200 --> 00:09:02.375
I know that the lot of
researchers work with Ookla,

00:09:02.375 --> 00:09:03.920
who produce Speedtest.

00:09:03.920 --> 00:09:05.960
And they do share their data.

00:09:05.960 --> 00:09:07.525
And they do share their
methodology.

00:09:07.525 --> 00:09:09.850
But it's a little harder
for everyone to get in

00:09:09.850 --> 00:09:12.060
there and do that.

00:09:12.060 --> 00:09:15.410
So one of the things that we
pride ourselves on is that we

00:09:15.410 --> 00:09:17.100
have a lot of unaggregated
data.

00:09:17.100 --> 00:09:19.070
And it's completely open.

00:09:19.070 --> 00:09:21.360
And because all of the tools
are open-source, and the

00:09:21.360 --> 00:09:24.290
platform is open-source, the
methodology is, therefore,

00:09:24.290 --> 00:09:27.530
open and freely-available for
anyone to dig into and to

00:09:27.530 --> 00:09:30.900
criticize, if need be.

00:09:30.900 --> 00:09:33.470
DEREK SLATER: What's something
that's surprised you as you've

00:09:33.470 --> 00:09:35.070
gotten to work with data,
or play around with it?

00:09:35.070 --> 00:09:40.380
Something that stood out as
you've dug into it yourself?

00:09:40.380 --> 00:09:41.665
DOMINIC HAMON: Well, one of the
interesting things that

00:09:41.665 --> 00:09:46.410
I've been working on recently is
looking at the geolocation

00:09:46.410 --> 00:09:48.630
of all of our tests, where
they're coming from.

00:09:48.630 --> 00:09:50.645
And the reason for that is to
try and determine where it

00:09:50.645 --> 00:09:53.750
would be good to build new
servers, to make sure that we

00:09:53.750 --> 00:09:56.230
have really good coverage
around the world.

00:09:56.230 --> 00:10:00.050
And so I've been working on a
visualization that plots all

00:10:00.050 --> 00:10:02.900
of the tests as pixels
on a map.

00:10:02.900 --> 00:10:06.410
And one of the interesting
things that came out of that

00:10:06.410 --> 00:10:10.600
was that we have 16 million,
12 million tests a month,

00:10:10.600 --> 00:10:11.760
something like that.

00:10:11.760 --> 00:10:15.680
And yet, there are giant
dark spots on the map.

00:10:15.680 --> 00:10:19.130
There are certain countries
where there is just no data

00:10:19.130 --> 00:10:19.830
coming out of that.

00:10:19.830 --> 00:10:23.280
And it's not clear if that's
because the data is being

00:10:23.280 --> 00:10:26.760
blocked on the way out or
because people there are not

00:10:26.760 --> 00:10:29.130
running the tests on the
platform or we just don't have

00:10:29.130 --> 00:10:30.270
awareness there.

00:10:30.270 --> 00:10:32.190
One of things that does surprise
me the other way,

00:10:32.190 --> 00:10:35.240
though, is that there's a
lot of very small and

00:10:35.240 --> 00:10:37.880
out-of-the-way countries that
are doing an awful lot of

00:10:37.880 --> 00:10:40.860
tests, many, many more
than I would expect.

00:10:40.860 --> 00:10:42.700
And so that gives us a clue of
where to put other servers.

00:10:42.700 --> 00:10:45.810
But it's also just really
interesting to see how broadly

00:10:45.810 --> 00:10:48.950
spread this is, in terms of
people wanting to know what

00:10:48.950 --> 00:10:51.411
the state of their
internet is.

00:10:51.411 --> 00:10:52.130
DEREK SLATER: That's great.

00:10:52.130 --> 00:10:53.850
So we've now talked about
Measurement Lab.

00:10:53.850 --> 00:10:57.350
One tool for empowering users
with a way to understand what

00:10:57.350 --> 00:10:59.970
the quality and speed of their
broadband connection is so

00:10:59.970 --> 00:11:03.500
they can make informed choices
and so that researchers,

00:11:03.500 --> 00:11:06.210
innovators, policymakers can
make informed decisions about

00:11:06.210 --> 00:11:07.630
broadband internet access.

00:11:07.630 --> 00:11:09.560
Now we're going to turn things
over Dorothy Chou, who's going

00:11:09.560 --> 00:11:12.520
to look at another set of
transparency tools.

00:11:12.520 --> 00:11:17.060
This set looks at Google's
Transparency Report, which

00:11:17.060 --> 00:11:17.800
she'll tell you about.

00:11:17.800 --> 00:11:21.325
It has to do with removal
requests and data requests

00:11:21.325 --> 00:11:24.720
that are made to Google from
governments and others.

00:11:24.720 --> 00:11:26.510
Dorothy, we'll hand
it over to you.

00:11:26.510 --> 00:11:27.660
DOROTHY CHOU: Thanks, Derek.

00:11:27.660 --> 00:11:30.560
So as Derek was saying, I work
on the Transparency Report,

00:11:30.560 --> 00:11:34.650
which is a site that shows when
Google is asked to remove

00:11:34.650 --> 00:11:38.040
information, like a YouTube
video or a blog post from our

00:11:38.040 --> 00:11:41.010
services, or when we're asked
to hand over user data to

00:11:41.010 --> 00:11:42.430
different governments.

00:11:42.430 --> 00:11:44.890
Overall, we see a really
disturbing trend, which is

00:11:44.890 --> 00:11:48.550
that governments that censor the
internet have gone up from

00:11:48.550 --> 00:11:50.830
about four governments
about 10 years ago to

00:11:50.830 --> 00:11:53.060
42 governments today.

00:11:53.060 --> 00:11:57.560
And 150 different countries have
basically been home to

00:11:57.560 --> 00:11:58.250
our services.

00:11:58.250 --> 00:12:02.290
And at that rate, more than 25%
of our services have been

00:12:02.290 --> 00:12:03.530
blocked at any given time.

00:12:03.530 --> 00:12:05.660
So this is a really big
concern for us.

00:12:05.660 --> 00:12:08.800
And we've created this report
precisely to help people track

00:12:08.800 --> 00:12:11.080
these different types of
trends to access to

00:12:11.080 --> 00:12:12.540
information online.

