00:12:20.650 --> 00:12:23.230
well as how we want to move
forward and how you guys can

00:12:23.230 --> 00:12:24.960
all engage with that.

00:12:24.960 --> 00:12:28.040
So the Transparency Report
has three basic parts.

00:12:28.040 --> 00:12:31.870
It has Traffic, Removal
Requests, and

00:12:31.870 --> 00:12:33.530
then User Data Requests.

00:12:33.530 --> 00:12:36.160
So if you take a look at the
page I'm showing right now,

00:12:36.160 --> 00:12:39.200
that shows the traffic, which
is the availability of our

00:12:39.200 --> 00:12:41.130
services in about 150 different

00:12:41.130 --> 00:12:42.870
countries around the world.

00:12:42.870 --> 00:12:46.010
You can see right now on the
homepage when Syria went

00:12:46.010 --> 00:12:48.170
completely offline last week.

00:12:48.170 --> 00:12:51.190
You can also see the different
trends around the Arab Spring

00:12:51.190 --> 00:12:55.140
early last year, particularly
with Egypt and Libya, as well

00:12:55.140 --> 00:12:57.450
as certain things about
infrastructure.

00:12:57.450 --> 00:13:01.490
So for example, when a
70-year-old woman in Armenia

00:13:01.490 --> 00:13:04.960
decided to scavenge copper and
cut the cable that carried the

00:13:04.960 --> 00:13:08.230
internet between Georgia and
Armenia and then cut off the

00:13:08.230 --> 00:13:09.950
internet access to both
of those countries

00:13:09.950 --> 00:13:11.730
for about six hours.

00:13:11.730 --> 00:13:14.680
And there are also some
encouraging trends, like when

00:13:14.680 --> 00:13:17.430
Myanmar decided to lift their
ban on foreign news sites, and

00:13:17.430 --> 00:13:19.270
when YouTube became accessible
for the first

00:13:19.270 --> 00:13:21.060
time in quite a while.

00:13:21.060 --> 00:13:23.970
And this traffic tool is
actually updated in real time.

00:13:23.970 --> 00:13:25.380
So you can follow along.

00:13:25.380 --> 00:13:28.090
And if you wanted to see if
Blogger was available in the

00:13:28.090 --> 00:13:32.630
UK yesterday or today, you could
do that really easily.

00:13:32.630 --> 00:13:35.170
Our second feature is called
Removal Requests, where we

00:13:35.170 --> 00:13:38.210
show the number of times we're
asked by governments or

00:13:38.210 --> 00:13:40.870
copyright owners to remove
information, like search

00:13:40.870 --> 00:13:44.670
results, YouTube videos, or blog
posts from our services.

00:13:44.670 --> 00:13:47.530
And what this really shows is
some interesting trends.

00:13:47.530 --> 00:13:50.660
For example, our Government
Requests Report, which I'm

00:13:50.660 --> 00:13:54.630
showing right now, shows
different trends about the

00:13:54.630 --> 00:13:57.670
effects of laws on our products
and services and

00:13:57.670 --> 00:13:59.710
whether or not you can access
different types of

00:13:59.710 --> 00:14:00.820
information.

00:14:00.820 --> 00:14:04.670
Sometimes it can lead to some
unintended consequences on the

00:14:04.670 --> 00:14:06.390
free flow of information.

00:14:06.390 --> 00:14:09.040
For example, in Brazil,
there's a very broad

00:14:09.040 --> 00:14:13.190
defamation law that sometimes
will cause more requests to be

00:14:13.190 --> 00:14:16.530
removed under the category of
defamation, which you can see

00:14:16.530 --> 00:14:19.510
accounts for the vast majority
of the requests that we've

00:14:19.510 --> 00:14:22.560
received since July 2010.

00:14:22.560 --> 00:14:25.290
And this tool updated
every six months.

00:14:25.290 --> 00:14:29.020
We also recently launched a
copyright feature this year

00:14:29.020 --> 00:14:31.980
that shows the number of search
results that copyright

00:14:31.980 --> 00:14:35.330
owners or organizations that
represent them ask us to

00:14:35.330 --> 00:14:38.450
remove because they allegedly
link to infringing content.

00:14:38.450 --> 00:14:40.440
And this is updated
every 24 hours.

00:14:40.440 --> 00:14:42.420
And what you can see is that
from the time we started

00:14:42.420 --> 00:14:46.510
reporting this information
back in July 2011-- or

00:14:46.510 --> 00:14:47.870
recording it this way--

00:14:47.870 --> 00:14:53.120
we went from just over 100,000
URLs being removed every week,

00:14:53.120 --> 00:14:59.550
all the way to more than 2.5
million different URLs being

00:14:59.550 --> 00:15:02.470
removed on a weekly
basis, recently.

00:15:02.470 --> 00:15:05.190
So it's really important to be
looking at this tool to figure

00:15:05.190 --> 00:15:08.140
out different data points when
it comes to copyright

00:15:08.140 --> 00:15:09.380
regulation.

00:15:09.380 --> 00:15:12.390
And this tool is updated
every 24 hours.

00:15:12.390 --> 00:15:15.380
We also have a third feature
which shows the number of

00:15:15.380 --> 00:15:20.450
times that governments have
asked us to hand over user

00:15:20.450 --> 00:15:22.230
information in different
criminal cases.

00:15:22.230 --> 00:15:24.830
And you can see that you can
sort this in different ways.

00:15:24.830 --> 00:15:28.460
For example, you can sort it by
the number of requests, the

00:15:28.460 --> 00:15:32.220
percentage of times where we
produced either some data that

00:15:32.220 --> 00:15:35.650
they requested or all of it, as
well as how many people or

00:15:35.650 --> 00:15:39.940
accounts were specified and
affected by these requests.

00:15:39.940 --> 00:15:42.880
Last month in particular, we
actually released new data for

00:15:42.880 --> 00:15:47.520
both government requests to
remove information or to get

00:15:47.520 --> 00:15:48.920
user information.

00:15:48.920 --> 00:15:50.990
And the interesting thing
about this particular

00:15:50.990 --> 00:15:53.060
reporting period is that
we saw government

00:15:53.060 --> 00:15:55.930
surveillance on the rise.

00:15:55.930 --> 00:15:58.990
Since we started reporting about
government surveillance

00:15:58.990 --> 00:16:04.060
or government access to user
information in 2010, we've

00:16:04.060 --> 00:16:06.770
actually seen the number of
user information requests

00:16:06.770 --> 00:16:09.650
almost double in that
time period.

00:16:09.650 --> 00:16:11.440
And that's really concerning
to us.

00:16:11.440 --> 00:16:13.250
And I'll share some more
anecdotes to basically

00:16:13.250 --> 00:16:14.940
illustrate my point.

00:16:14.940 --> 00:16:18.810
So you can see on this page that
the US continues to top

00:16:18.810 --> 00:16:21.960
the list of countries that
make user data requests.

00:16:21.960 --> 00:16:25.140
And it's clear that basically
the law that governs access to

00:16:25.140 --> 00:16:28.490
user information, which was
passed in 1986-- and that's

00:16:28.490 --> 00:16:31.090
well before any of us were
using the internet in the

00:16:31.090 --> 00:16:33.080
capacity that we are today--

00:16:33.080 --> 00:16:36.400
hasn't really kept up with how
users are engaging online.

00:16:36.400 --> 00:16:39.240
And it doesn't really provide
the types of protections we'd

00:16:39.240 --> 00:16:41.240
like to see in place
for users.

00:16:41.240 --> 00:16:43.310
And we're hoping that these
numbers help contribute to a

00:16:43.310 --> 00:16:46.980
conversation about how to update
that law in order to

00:16:46.980 --> 00:16:50.110
uphold individual rights to
privacy while also ensuring

00:16:50.110 --> 00:16:51.860
that governments have
the legal tools they

00:16:51.860 --> 00:16:53.890
need to fight crime.

00:16:53.890 --> 00:16:57.770
You can also see that 16
different EU countries made

00:16:57.770 --> 00:17:01.190
1/3 of all of the user data
requests that we received

00:17:01.190 --> 00:17:02.750
earlier this year.

00:17:02.750 --> 00:17:05.079
And out of the top 10 countries
that have requested

00:17:05.079 --> 00:17:07.410
data, five of them
are from Europe--

00:17:07.410 --> 00:17:12.200
France, Germany, the UK,
Italy, and Spain.

00:17:12.200 --> 00:17:15.290
Interestingly, in Asia you
can see that India is the

00:17:15.290 --> 00:17:18.650
second-highest government
requesting user information.

00:17:18.650 --> 00:17:21.430
And that accounts for more than
10% of all the user data

00:17:21.430 --> 00:17:24.400
requests we received in the
first six months of this year.

00:17:24.400 --> 00:17:26.950
And you can also see that out
of the top 10 countries that

00:17:26.950 --> 00:17:30.000
made user data requests, only
one of them, Brazil, is in

00:17:30.000 --> 00:17:31.770
South America.

00:17:31.770 --> 00:17:35.200
On the government requests for
removal side, we actually saw

00:17:35.200 --> 00:17:39.220
that if you look at it over
time, the request to remove

00:17:39.220 --> 00:17:42.110
content from our services
has been largely flat.

00:17:42.110 --> 00:17:44.540
But it has actually spiked in
this particular reporting

00:17:44.540 --> 00:17:53.790
period in the first half of
2012, when we got just less

00:17:53.790 --> 00:17:58.640
than 2,000 requests to remove
information from our services.

00:17:58.640 --> 00:17:59.950
And all of this stuff
is actually

00:17:59.950 --> 00:18:01.430
available in download form.

00:18:01.430 --> 00:18:04.230
So you can actually download
these different data sets in

00:18:04.230 --> 00:18:06.320
CSVs and play around with
them and see different

00:18:06.320 --> 00:18:07.950
visualizations.

00:18:07.950 --> 00:18:10.830
What we're really hoping to
do with this data is to

00:18:10.830 --> 00:18:12.970
contribute to a public
conversation about how

00:18:12.970 --> 00:18:16.090
different laws and government
behaviors influence access to

00:18:16.090 --> 00:18:17.970
information online.

00:18:17.970 --> 00:18:21.820
Many of the laws, we believe,
that are in place are actually

00:18:21.820 --> 00:18:24.450
unintentionally resulting in
overbroad censorship or

00:18:24.450 --> 00:18:24.950
surveillance.

00:18:24.950 --> 00:18:27.510
So it's important to really
look at the data as

00:18:27.510 --> 00:18:30.080
governments are creating
these different laws.

00:18:30.080 --> 00:18:32.220
And we're hoping that policy
makers can actually see what's

00:18:32.220 --> 00:18:35.880
happening through Google
Services, and adjust and

00:18:35.880 --> 00:18:38.370
reform those laws to make sure
they're actually relevant and

00:18:38.370 --> 00:18:42.400
effective and working in
the public interest.

00:18:42.400 --> 00:18:45.120
So finally, what do we need
to actually move forward?

00:18:45.120 --> 00:18:46.760
Well, we would love if
governments would be more

00:18:46.760 --> 00:18:49.920
transparent about when and why
they want us to block access

00:18:49.920 --> 00:18:55.670
to different information or
request user information.

00:18:55.670 --> 00:18:58.570
An important part of democracy
is that people are really able

00:18:58.570 --> 00:19:00.580
to hold these governments
accountable.

00:19:00.580 --> 00:19:02.890
And so that if they want to
change the law, they can do so

00:19:02.890 --> 00:19:04.420
democratically.

00:19:04.420 --> 00:19:07.920
The harm is really coming when
there's no checks or balances.

00:19:07.920 --> 00:19:10.140
And there's some danger of scope
creep when there is lack

00:19:10.140 --> 00:19:11.490
of disclosure.

00:19:11.490 --> 00:19:14.820
For example, we really worked
hard on a document called the

00:19:14.820 --> 00:19:17.150
Stockholm Principles, which
you can actually find at

00:19:17.150 --> 00:19:19.070
stockholdprinciples.org.

00:19:19.070 --> 00:19:21.230
And it offers some basic
guidelines about different

00:19:21.230 --> 00:19:23.080
types of government transparency
reporting.

00:19:23.080 --> 00:19:25.730
And we really need more
leadership to commit to that.

00:19:25.730 --> 00:19:28.610
And it's mostly because the
effects of these laws that

00:19:28.610 --> 00:19:31.120
directly impacts censorship and
surveillance are really

00:19:31.120 --> 00:19:32.760
quickly becoming entrenched.

00:19:32.760 --> 00:19:35.120
And so we need the public to
know and be more engaged on

00:19:35.120 --> 00:19:38.180
these issues and confirm if
those laws and policies are

00:19:38.180 --> 00:19:40.660
actually working in their
best interests.

00:19:40.660 --> 00:19:42.150
And the only way we can do
that is through more

00:19:42.150 --> 00:19:43.600
transparency.

00:19:43.600 --> 00:19:45.990
And to that end, we'd actually
love for more companies to

00:19:45.990 --> 00:19:48.470
join this effort as well, so we
can get a better picture of

00:19:48.470 --> 00:19:50.200
what's actually going online.

00:19:50.200 --> 00:19:51.970
Our view is pretty limited
and incomplete.

00:19:51.970 --> 00:19:54.060
We can only see what's happening
on Google Services.

00:19:54.060 --> 00:19:55.780
And so we need more
data points.

00:19:55.780 --> 00:19:59.450
So for example, a government
could issue us two requests in

00:19:59.450 --> 00:20:02.150
a reporting period, but another
company 1,000, and you

00:20:02.150 --> 00:20:03.670
really wouldn't be able
to see the difference.

00:20:03.670 --> 00:20:05.830
So we're hoping that more and
more companies do that.

00:20:05.830 --> 00:20:08.000
And recently, I think four
different companies have

00:20:08.000 --> 00:20:10.930
really stepped up to the plate
and joined us in that effort,

00:20:10.930 --> 00:20:14.830
including Twitter and Dropbox.

00:20:14.830 --> 00:20:17.470
And then finally, we really
need more researchers and

00:20:17.470 --> 00:20:20.300
developers like you all to look
at our data, download

00:20:20.300 --> 00:20:23.510
those CSVs, really take a look
at it and build on top of it,

00:20:23.510 --> 00:20:25.790
and find the different trends
that you can see, and really

00:20:25.790 --> 00:20:28.030
call things out like they are.

00:20:28.030 --> 00:20:30.000
There's no way that we can move
forward in this effort

00:20:30.000 --> 00:20:30.600
without you all.

00:20:30.600 --> 00:20:32.930
So I really encourage
you to do that.

00:20:32.930 --> 00:20:33.362
DEREK SLATER: Great.

00:20:33.362 --> 00:20:34.660
Thanks, Dorothy.

00:20:34.660 --> 00:20:37.460
And just a couple questions
about the report.

00:20:37.460 --> 00:20:40.900
When did Google start, and you
start working on this?

00:20:40.900 --> 00:20:43.520
DOROTHY CHOU: We started
publishing the information for

00:20:43.520 --> 00:20:47.490
government requests
in spring of 2010.

00:20:47.490 --> 00:20:49.450
DEREK SLATER: What was the
initial motivation to sort of

00:20:49.450 --> 00:20:52.170
open up the kimono and tell
people a little bit more about

00:20:52.170 --> 00:20:53.270
what was going on?

00:20:53.270 --> 00:20:55.130
DOROTHY CHOU: Well, I think we
started to see more and more

00:20:55.130 --> 00:20:57.430
requests come in from different
governments, to both

00:20:57.430 --> 00:20:59.770
remove information from our
services and also for user

00:20:59.770 --> 00:21:00.230
information.

00:21:00.230 --> 00:21:03.290
And we were thinking, unless we
are more open about this,

00:21:03.290 --> 00:21:05.100
people aren't going to
understand the collateral

00:21:05.100 --> 00:21:06.620
effects of these different
laws that

00:21:06.620 --> 00:21:07.690
are around the world.

00:21:07.690 --> 00:21:10.860
And so we wanted to provide them
with that data point to

00:21:10.860 --> 00:21:13.030
basically decide, is this
actually working the way I

00:21:13.030 --> 00:21:13.650
want it to?

00:21:13.650 --> 00:21:15.530
And if not, how do I
change that law?

00:21:15.530 --> 00:21:16.290
How do I fix it?

00:21:16.290 --> 00:21:19.380
And how do I become a part of
that political process?

00:21:19.380 --> 00:21:21.910
DEREK SLATER: And what else--
so, developers can go and play

00:21:21.910 --> 00:21:24.990
with the CSVs to visualize the
data, look for trends there.

00:21:24.990 --> 00:21:27.470
What else can the developer
community do to make an impact

00:21:27.470 --> 00:21:28.020
in this effort?

00:21:28.020 --> 00:21:30.060
Are there the other tools that
you think, gosh, I wish

00:21:30.060 --> 00:21:34.090
somebody was building this to
help users or help others

00:21:34.090 --> 00:21:35.935
really understand what the
nature of this issue is?

00:21:35.935 --> 00:21:36.960
DOROTHY CHOU: Yeah,
absolutely.

00:21:36.960 --> 00:21:39.610
So there's a site called
herdict.org.

00:21:39.610 --> 00:21:43.550
And it's a more of a crowdsource
tool that allows

00:21:43.550 --> 00:21:46.090
users to report, this site isn't
working for me, or I

00:21:46.090 --> 00:21:48.150
can't access it from
a given country.

00:21:48.150 --> 00:21:50.550
And we would love to see
developers take those

00:21:50.550 --> 00:21:52.790
different data sources that
are available online, like

00:21:52.790 --> 00:21:56.600
herdict, like our report, like
Twitter's report, for example,

00:21:56.600 --> 00:21:58.930
and put those all together to
create a better picture of

00:21:58.930 --> 00:22:01.200
what information flows
look like online.

00:22:01.200 --> 00:22:03.700
We don't really have that
collaborative reporting

00:22:03.700 --> 00:22:04.330
feature yet.

00:22:04.330 --> 00:22:06.400
So anything that developers
can do to bring those

00:22:06.400 --> 00:22:10.022
information data points
together, that would be great.

00:22:10.022 --> 00:22:12.240
DEREK SLATER: Well, that brings
us to the end of this

00:22:12.240 --> 00:22:16.100
episode of "Free and Open."
We've got to learn about some

00:22:16.100 --> 00:22:20.220
ways that users can understand
how their broadband internet

00:22:20.220 --> 00:22:25.240
connection works and what sort
of requests that government or

00:22:25.240 --> 00:22:27.330
others are making to
remove content or

00:22:27.330 --> 00:22:29.130
disclose data on the web.

00:22:29.130 --> 00:22:32.740
Hope here is that we can
empower more users to

00:22:32.740 --> 00:22:35.210
understand what's going on and
through transparency, help

00:22:35.210 --> 00:22:36.740
have a richer conversation
about the

00:22:36.740 --> 00:22:37.680
future of the internet.

00:22:37.680 --> 00:22:41.620
Tomorrow we'll be back to talk
a bit about entrepreneurship

00:22:41.620 --> 00:22:43.720
on the free and open internet.

00:22:43.720 --> 00:22:45.370
But that's it for
today's episode.

